Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of his bunk, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook fastened to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he calmly left the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before slowly opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the preset alarm, because half the time it didn't work — all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Sure," replied Cohren.
"What have you planned to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and armed.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?", asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up with today. Second, the first shock troops up are the first ones at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. A loud, wailing alarm blared inside the barracks. He heard commotion and chaos from within.
"Good grief, Valturi," Nemic said. "One would have thought they'd have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their group and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company emerged en masse. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Excuse me, sir, why do you insist on waking us up like this?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard alarms are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal belongings," he continued. As the first lieutenant and the commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company alongside the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We will not be returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete the final checks and to retrieve rations for the day."
Members of the Exodus company scattered. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Initially, they were divided into two separate companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company, and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly because of the reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the numerous floodlights of the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had employed both aerial and ground Wild Weasel attacks to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, smoking his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of fighting changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Damn it. The situation is getting worse on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "In any case, we're leaving with the first armored squad, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Did Shaw get us a ride?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Sure. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable either."
Cohren brought his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone while adjusting his backpack. "All company units, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik had all been low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed so long ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. At that time, they had all been squadron leaders. But Craith had now been commanding the second platoon for a week, following the discharge of the previous commander, who had been wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of approximately eight main battle tanks and four Strykers. Their crews were busy ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored company commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
